  "summary": "Detective Constable Craddock interrogates Laura Brouster regarding her history of making threats against Marina Gregg. Craddock reveals that Brouster had previously threatened to kill Marina and notes that Brouster once shot and killed Eddie Groves during an argument. Brouster dismisses the accusations, arguing that her words were taken out of proportion and that it would be unrealistic for her to travel to England specifically to poison Marina’s cocktail. She characterizes Marina as a fickle woman who struggled with personal issues, including failed attempts to raise adopted children. Craddock observes that while an obvious attempt on Marina's life occurred, an unknown woman was mistakenly killed instead.\n\nLater, Craddock visits Adwick Fenn at the Duchester, Suite 190. Fenn discusses the Victorian style of Gossington Hall and speculates that the drug in the cocktail was intended for Marina. He suggests that Lina Brown might have had a motive involving a film role, though he posits the poisoning might have been intended to scare Marina rather than kill her. When Craddock confronts Fenn about rumors that he was once obsessively in love with Marina and that she feared him, Fenn admits to a past obsession. However, he denies making any threats, claiming his previous interference with Marina's film career was a commercial decision made to protect his investment. He dismisses Marina's fear as childish and maintains that he moves on quickly from disappointments.",
